<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>What to Do If You're Paid Late</h1>
  <p>Whether you're a vendor with an overdue invoice or an employee whose paycheck is late, the recovery process follows a clear escalation path. Most disputes resolve before reaching litigation — the key is moving through the steps promptly, because statutes of limitations run, and penalties often stop accruing once certain thresholds are hit.</p>
  <p><em>Reviewed by our editorial team. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <h2>For B2B / overdue invoices</h2>

  <h3>Step 1: Document everything before reaching out</h3>
  <p>Before you send anything, organize your documentation: the original invoice, signed contract or purchase order, evidence of delivery or completion, any prior payment correspondence, and the calculation of what's owed including late fees and interest. You need to be able to hand this to a collections attorney or small-claims court on short notice. Disputes that fail often fail because the creditor can't prove delivery or accepted terms — not because the money wasn't owed.</p>

  <h3>Step 2: Send a clear, professional reminder</h3>
  <p>Many late payments are genuine oversight — a routing slip that missed a desk, an accounting system delay, a staffing change in AP. A polite email referencing the invoice number, original due date, and current balance owed often resolves the issue within a few business days. Keep the tone professional — no threats at this stage. State what's owed and ask when you can expect payment. Document the date sent and any response received.</p>
  <p>If you have a contractual "cure period" before late fees kick in, this communication is what starts that clock. Send it on time so you don't inadvertently waive late fees by failing to give proper notice.</p>

  <h3>Step 3: Send a formal demand letter</h3>
  <p>If the informal reminder produces no payment within 7–10 days, escalate to a formal demand letter. A demand letter should include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>The original invoice number, date, and amount</li>
    <li>Your contractual payment terms (net-30, net-60, etc.) and the date payment became overdue</li>
    <li>Current balance — original invoice amount plus any contractual late fees and accrued interest, with the calculation shown</li>
    <li>A clear deadline for payment — typically 10–14 days from the date of the letter</li>
    <li>Explicit statement of consequences: referral to collections, credit reporting, or legal action</li>
    <li>Your preferred payment method and account information</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Send by certified mail with return receipt, and keep a copy. Email is fine for the initial conversation; certified mail is the evidentiary record. The demand letter creates the paper trail you'll need if this goes to collections or court.</p>

  <h3>Step 4: Negotiate — even if it's awkward</h3>
  <p>Many commercial disputes settle before anyone files anything. If the debtor contacts you after the demand letter, listen to what they're saying. A genuine cash-flow crisis that produces a realistic payment plan — with interest still accruing — is often better than a prolonged legal fight over a customer who can't pay anyway. If you agree to a payment plan, get it in writing and signed before you stop collection actions.</p>
  <p>If the debtor disputes the invoice amount, evaluate the dispute honestly. A meritless dispute designed to delay doesn't pause late fees in most states. A legitimate dispute about the amount owed may. Don't waive late fees on the disputed amount without getting something in return — a quick partial payment, a signed acknowledgment of the undisputed balance, or a firm settlement.</p>

  <h3>Step 5: Consider mediation or arbitration</h3>
  <p>If your contract includes an arbitration clause, you're likely required to arbitrate rather than litigate. Some states have free or low-cost commercial mediation programs for disputes under certain thresholds. Mediation is non-binding but often faster and cheaper than court. If there's a genuine business relationship worth preserving, mediation avoids the adversarial posture that litigation creates.</p>
  <p>If no arbitration clause exists and mediation isn't productive, the next step is court.</p>

  <h3>Step 6: File suit — small claims for smaller amounts</h3>
  <p>Small claims court is designed for disputes without attorneys and moves faster than civil court. Limits vary by state:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>California: $12,500 for individuals, $6,250 for businesses</li>
    <li>New York: $10,000</li>
    <li>Texas: $20,000</li>
    <li>Florida: $8,000</li>
    <li>Federal threshold for diversity jurisdiction (federal court): $75,000+</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Above small-claims limits, you need to weigh the economics: attorney's fees typically run $200–$500/hour, and a commercial collection case can cost $3,000–$15,000 in fees before you see a judgment. If your contract includes a prevailing-party attorney's-fee clause, that changes the calculus — if you win, the debtor pays your fees.</p>

  <h3>Step 7: Collections agency (last resort)</h3>
  <p>Selling or assigning the debt to a collections agency typically recovers 30–70% of face value, depending on the debt's age, the debtor's creditworthiness, and the industry. It ends your direct involvement and transfers the headache, but it's the lowest-recovery option. Consider this only when direct collection and litigation aren't economically viable — usually small debts from judgment-proof debtors.</p>

  <h2>For employment / late final paycheck</h2>

  <h3>Step 1: Calculate what you're owed before doing anything</h3>
  <p>Know your number before you contact anyone. Use our <a href="/">calculator</a> to estimate the amount owed. For California: unpaid wages + waiting-time penalty (daily wage &times; days late, capped at 30 days). For Massachusetts: unpaid wages &times; 3 + attorney's fees. For Illinois: unpaid wages + 1% per day + fees. For other states: check the <a href="/guides/final-paycheck-deadlines-by-state">final paycheck deadlines by state</a> guide for your state's penalty structure.</p>
  <p>Also check the statute of limitations. In California, you have three years to file a wage claim under Labor Code § 203; four years if you're filing a contract claim. In Massachusetts, three years. Missing the deadline forfeits the claim.</p>

  <h3>Step 2: Send a written demand to HR or payroll</h3>
  <p>Email your former employer's HR department or whoever handled your payroll. Reference the applicable statute (e.g., "California Labor Code § 203 required payment of my final wages immediately at termination on [date]"). State the specific amount owed — final wages plus penalty calculation. Set a response deadline of 5–7 business days. Keep it professional and factual. Do not threaten personal consequences or make claims you can't back up.</p>
  <p>Many employers pay immediately when confronted with a specific statutory citation and a clear number. The ones who don't are often either disputing the calculation or have decided to litigate — in which case your demand letter is valuable evidence of willfulness (which triggers higher penalties in some states).</p>

  <h3>Step 3: File with your state labor agency — free</h3>
  <p>This is the most underused option. Every state has a labor agency with a free wage-claim process that doesn't require an attorney. In California, that's the Labor Commissioner's Office (DLSE). In New York, the Department of Labor. In Massachusetts, the Attorney General's Fair Labor Division. Filing is free, investigation is conducted by agency staff, and the employer is required to respond.</p>
  <p>The agency process has limits — it's slower than court, it can't always force employers to pay, and it doesn't always maximize your recovery. But for smaller amounts, it's often the most practical path. And filing with the agency typically tolls (pauses) the statute of limitations while the claim is pending.</p>

  <h3>Step 4: Consult an employment attorney</h3>
  <p>For larger amounts — anything over $2,000–$3,000 — it's worth a free consultation with an employment attorney who handles wage claims. Most work on contingency for wage cases, meaning they take a percentage of the recovery (typically 30–40%) and charge nothing upfront. Because most state wage statutes include mandatory attorney's-fee shifting for successful plaintiffs, attorneys can often recover their fees from the employer on top of the damages.</p>
  <p>An attorney can pursue claims the labor agency can't — including injunctive relief, class actions for systemic wage violations, and coordinated federal/state claims. If you've found that your employer has a pattern of late final paychecks, a class action may be possible, and the economics shift dramatically in your favor.</p>

  <h3>Step 5: Federal FLSA claim if applicable</h3>
  <p>The federal Fair Labor Standards Act requires timely payment of wages. For willful violations, workers can recover unpaid wages, an equal amount in liquidated damages, plus attorney's fees. The FLSA is a backstop — state remedies are typically more favorable for final-paycheck claims, but you can pursue both simultaneously in most jurisdictions. File with the US Department of Labor's Wage and Hour Division, or file a federal suit directly.</p>

  <h2>What NOT to do (either context)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Don't make threats you can't back up.</strong> "I'll sue you tomorrow" is an empty threat if you're not prepared to act on it. It reduces your credibility and signals that you're not serious about enforcement.</li>
    <li><strong>Don't disparage the debtor publicly.</strong> Posting on social media about an employer or customer before the dispute is resolved creates defamation exposure, even if everything you say is true. Document privately; litigate publicly only through proper channels.</li>
    <li><strong>Don't accept partial payment as full settlement without a written release.</strong> If a debtor sends you a check marked "payment in full" or makes you sign a release, that check can extinguish your right to the remaining balance and all penalties in some states. If partial payment is offered as settlement, negotiate the terms explicitly before accepting anything. Get any settlement in writing, signed, with the specific amounts and releases spelled out.</li>
    <li><strong>Don't wait past the statute of limitations.</strong> For written contracts, typically 4–6 years in most states. For employment wage claims, often 2–3 years. For California waiting-time penalties under § 203, three years. The clock starts from the date payment was due, not from when you discovered the nonpayment.</li>
    <li><strong>Don't stop documenting.</strong> Every day you wait without a written record makes your case weaker. Keep copies of all invoices, emails, texts, and records of verbal conversations (date, time, what was said, who was present). Memory fades; documentation doesn't.</li>
  </ul>
</BaseLayout>
